###  https://w3id.org/emmo#Tesla
:Tesla rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                :EMMO_e9ffc696_5228_4ff9_8a60_0f5e05e9931b ,
                :EMMO_ec903946_ddc9_464a_903c_7373e0d1eeb5 ;
       :EMMO_daf7a9b7_18ef_4e73_9fb9_75adfd9800e8 "T" ;
       skos:prefLabel "Tesla"@en ;
       schema:unitCode "D33" ;
       :dbpediaReference "http://dbpedia.org/resource/Tesla"^^xsd:anyURI ;
       :elucidation "SI unit for magnetic flux density or induction."@en ;
       :iupacReference "https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.T06283" ;
       :note """The SI unit of flux density (or field intensity) for magnetic fields (also called the magnetic induction). The intensity of a magnetic field can be measured by placing a current-carrying conductor in the field. The magnetic field exerts a force on the conductor, a force which depends on the amount of the current and on the length of the conductor. One tesla is defined as the field intensity generating one newton of force per ampere of current per meter of conductor. Equivalently, one tesla represents a magnetic flux density of one weber per square meter of area. A field of one tesla is quite strong: the strongest fields available in laboratories are about 20 teslas, and the Earth's magnetic flux density, at its surface, is about 50 microteslas. The tesla, defined in 1958, honors the Serbian-American electrical engineer Nikola Tesla (1856-1943), whose work in electromagnetic induction led to the first practical generators and motors using alternating current.

-- QUDT"""@en ,
             "T = V·s·m⁻² = N/(A·m) = Wb/m²" ;
       :qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/T" ;
       :ucumCode "T" ;
       :wikipediaReference "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tesla_(unit)"^^xsd:anyURI .


###  https://w3id.org/emmo#Volt
:Volt rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
               :EMMO_2e7e5796_4a80_4d73_bb84_f31138446c0c ,
               :EMMO_e9ffc696_5228_4ff9_8a60_0f5e05e9931b ;
      :EMMO_daf7a9b7_18ef_4e73_9fb9_75adfd9800e8 "V" ;
      skos:prefLabel "Volt"@en ;
      schema:unitCode "VLT" ;
      :dbpediaReference "http://dbpedia.org/resource/Volt"^^xsd:anyURI ;
      :elucidation "SI unit for electric potential difference."@en ;
      :iupacReference "https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.V06634" ;
      :note "The volt is the unit of electric potential difference—electric potential difference is also known as voltage. The size of 1 volt is officially defined as the potential difference between two points of a wire carrying a current of 1 ampere when the power dissipated in the wire is 1 watt."@en ;
      :qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/V" ;
      :ucumCode "V" ;
      :wikipediaReference "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volt?oldid=494812083"^^xsd:anyURI .


###  https://w3id.org/emmo#Watt
:Watt rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
               :EMMO_c8d084ad_f88e_4596_8e4d_982c6655ce6f ,
               :EMMO_e9ffc696_5228_4ff9_8a60_0f5e05e9931b ;
      :EMMO_daf7a9b7_18ef_4e73_9fb9_75adfd9800e8 "W" ;
      skos:prefLabel "Watt"@en ;
      schema:unitCode "WTT" ;
      :dbpediaReference "http://dbpedia.org/resource/Watt" ;
      :elucidation "SI unit for power."@en ;
      :iupacReference "https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.W06656" ;
      :note """The SI unit of power. Power is the rate at which work is done, or (equivalently) the rate at which energy is expended. One watt is equal to a power rate of one joule of work per second of time. This unit is used both in mechanics and in electricity, so it links the mechanical and electrical units to one another. In mechanical terms, one watt equals about 0.001 341 02 horsepower (hp) or 0.737 562 foot-pound per second (lbf/s). In electrical terms, one watt is the power produced by a current of one ampere flowing through an electric potential of one volt. The name of the unit honors James Watt (1736-1819), the British engineer whose improvements to the steam engine are often credited with igniting the Industrial Revolution.

-- QUDT"""@en ;
      :qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/W" ;
      :ucumCode "W" ;
      :wikipediaReference "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Watt?oldid=494906356"^^xsd:anyURI .


###  https://w3id.org/emmo#Weber
:Weber rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                :EMMO_4c49ab58_a6f6_409e_b849_f873ae1dcbee ,
                :EMMO_e9ffc696_5228_4ff9_8a60_0f5e05e9931b ;
       :EMMO_daf7a9b7_18ef_4e73_9fb9_75adfd9800e8 "Wb" ;
       skos:prefLabel "Weber"@en ;
       schema:unitCode "WEB" ;
       :dbpediaReference "http://dbpedia.org/resource/Weber"^^xsd:anyURI ;
       :elucidation "SI unit for magnetic flux."@en ;
       :iupacReference "https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.W06666" ;
       :note "The SI unit of magnetic flux. \"Flux\" is the rate (per unit of time) at which something crosses a surface perpendicular to the flow. The weber is a large unit, equal to 10⁸ maxwells, and practical fluxes are usually fractions of one weber. The weber is the magnetic flux which, linking a circuit of one turn, would produce in it an electromotive force of 1 volt if it were reduced to zero at a uniform rate in 1 second. In SI base units, the dimensions of the weber are (kg·m²)/(s²·A). The weber is commonly expressed in terms of other derived units as the Tesla-square meter (T·m²), volt-seconds (V·s), or joules per ampere (J/A)."@en ;
       :qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/WB" ;
       :ucumCode "Wb" ;
       :wikipediaReference "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weber_(unit)"^^xsd:anyURI .


[ owl:qualifiedCardinality "1"^^xsd:nonNegativeInteger
] .


